\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 12. Dimah \'97 Perpetual Blood Money and Diya Financing\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This is the most unexpected application. In Islamic jurisprudence, diya (blood money) is the compensation paid in cases of accidental killing or bodily harm. The amount is fixed by fiqh (currently valued at approximately $30,000\'96$100,000 depending on jurisdiction). Families unable to pay diya face imprisonment.\
A 
\f2\b diya takaful pool
\f0\b0  using the Ackerer framework: participants pay continuous premium \uc0\u954  \'d7 pool_share. At the random diya event \u952  (accident requiring payment), the pool pays out the required amount. The actuarially fair premium is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs26 \cf0 Premium = E[ diya_amount \'d7 1_\{accident at \uc0\u952 \} ] = diya_amount \'d7 Q_a(\u952  \u8804  T)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs24 \cf0 This is a stopping time problem with constant hazard rate \uc0\u954  (accident frequency). With \u953 =0, the premium is purely the probability-weighted expected payout. No interest. This converts a system that currently leads to imprisonment of innocent families into an actuarially sound, riba-free mutual insurance \'97 precisely what takaful is supposed to be.\
